#### Project details 

I am in the implementation phase of a new project to develop a game for Android mobile devices.  I already have a mobile app developed in Flutter/Dart at /home/daniel/work/puzzgameFlutter.       I am using the hexagonal architecture to have a clean separation between the logic of the app and the logic of game play.   Game play rendering and logic should be contained in an implementation dart class PuzzleGameModule (lib/game_module/puzzle_game_module.dart), see the class NookGameModule (lib/game_module/nook_game_module.dart) for an example of how this class should be structured and invoked by the main app.    The puzzle game should implement a layout consisting of a large view showing the partially completed puzzle, and beneath it a horizontally scrolling tray that contains all of the individual pieces, in a randomized order.      So the object of this game is for the user to select pieces from the tray and place those pieces in the location where they fit into the solution.   Each piece has a location where it belongs specified as row_col and encoded in the filename of the piece when it is stored in the asset folder in puzzle pack format.   Puzzle pack format is defined as follows: ### Puzzle pack format:

Each puzzle pack is delivered as a zip archive. After extraction, the folder structure is as follows:

puzzle_pack_name/

├── manifest.json                      # JSON file describing metadata for the pack

├── puzzle_01/

│   ├── preview.jpg                    # Preview image of the completed puzzle

│   └── layouts/

│       ├── 2x2/

│       │   ├── outline.svg

│       │   ├── outline-split.svg

│       │   └── pieces/

│       │       ├── 0_0.png

│       │       ├── 0_1.png

│       │       ├── 1_0.png

│       │       └── 1_1.png

│       ├── 16x16/

│       │   ├── outline.svg

│       │   └── pieces/

│       │       └── 0_0.png through 15_15.png

│       └── 32x32/

│           └── (same format)

├── puzzle_02/

│   └── (same structure)

Each layout contains:

- outline.svg: the vector outline of the jigsaw cut pattern

- preview-outline.png: the preview with the cut outline for reference

- pieces/: transparent PNG files, each representing a jigsaw piece

The puzzle pieces are named using the pattern X_Y.png based on their row and column in the grid (0-indexed). For example, 2_3.png is the piece at row 2, column 3. This naming allows a script to reconstruct the solved puzzle layout using the filenames and the solution.json which then maps the X_Y grid coordinate to pixel offsets within the original puzzle image.


